Isotopte Atom Count is the number of isotopes that are not most abundant for the corresponding chemical elements.  Isotopes are variants of a chemical element which differ in neutron number.  For example, among three isotopes of carbon (i.e., C-12, C-13, and C-14), the isotope atom count considers the C-13 and C-14 atoms, because C-12 is the most abundant isotope of carbon.

StringWithMarkup.String: Decomposition: < 0.5% after 1 day storage at 100 °C; < 0.5% after 7 days at 50 °C. The solid is stable to sunlight. Decomposition at 20 °C in aqueous solution after 21 days in the dark is: 4% at pH 5.8, 8% at pH 7, 26% at pH 9.

Reference: Worthing, C.R. and S.B. Walker (eds.). The Pesticide Manual - A World Compendium. 8th ed. Thornton Heath, UK: The British Crop Protection Council, 1987., p. 287

StringWithMarkup.String: Stable in acidic and neutral media (pH 2-7). Hydrolyzed in alkaline media above pH9. Light-sensitive when in solution, but stable to sunlight as a solid.

Reference: Hartley, D. and H. Kidd (eds.). The Agrochemicals Handbook. 2nd ed. Lechworth, Herts, England: The Royal Society of Chemistry, 1987., p. A148/Aug 87

StringWithMarkup.String: Diflubenzuron was stable in water and recoveries were 97% or better. Hydrolysis was very slow and produced p-chlorophenylurea. As PH and temperature increased, stability decreased.

StringWithMarkup.String: Under conditions approximating normal use, diflubenzuron was persistent on cotton plants and resistant to photodecomposition.
